# Product Outline

## Overview
As the VA Health & Benefits mobile app grows, the app needs a clear, scalable information architecture (IA) framework that defines where features live, how they are presented, and when they belong on the Home screen. This work establishes a shared model for app structure and Home screen placement so teams can make consistent, intentional decisions as new features are introduced.

This initiative is meant to create a durable, reusable foundation for feature placement across the mobile app. It should help protect the Home screen as high-value real estate, reduce ambiguity for teams, and improve navigability and predictability for Veterans.

## Problem Statement
As a Veteran, I want the app to be organized in a way that feels clear and predictable, so I can find what I need and understand why certain information appears on the Home screen versus elsewhere in the app.

As a feature team, I want clear criteria for feature placement and Home screen eligibility, so that I can make product and design decisions earlier and with less ambiguity.

As a platform team, we want a shared IA framework that scales with the app, so that new features can be introduced consistently without slowing delivery or creating one-off decisions.

## Desired User Outcomes

- *Why would a user want to use this?* Veterans benefit from a clearer, more intentional app structure that makes features easier to find and understand.
- *With this problem solved, what should users be able to do/achieve that they couldn't before?* Veterans should be able to navigate the app more confidently, understand the relative importance of what appears on the Home screen, and encounter a more predictable experience as the app evolves.

## Undesired User Outcomes

- Veterans have difficulty finding features because placement feels inconsistent.
- The Home screen becomes cluttered, noisy, or less useful as more features are added. 
- App structure feels unpredictable or changes in ways that reduce trust and efficiency. 

## Desired Business Outcomes

- *Why would your business want this to exist?* A shared IA model supports long-term product quality, reduces ambiguity for teams, and enables the app to scale more effectively as new functionality is added.
- *With this problem solved, what should your business be able to do/achieve that they couldn't before?* Teams should be able to place new features using documented guidance, align earlier on Home screen expectations, and make decisions that are easier to communicate and defend across product, design, and engineering.

## Undesired Business Outcomes

- Teams continue making one-off placement decisions without shared criteria.
- Home screen real estate is overused or used inconsistently.
- Delivery slows because teams need repeated alignment on where features belong.
- Existing features remain inconsistently organized, making the IA harder to scale over time.

---

## Measuring Success
This initiative will be successful if it results in a documented, reusable IA framework that defines app-level placement patterns, Home screen inclusion criteria, and feature hierarchy. It should also classify all current app features into a documented set of IA buckets and provide a clear rationale for Home screen prominence and ordering.

### Key Performance Indicators (KPIs)

- Percentage of existing app features reviewed and assigned to an IA bucket
- Completion and publication of Home screen placement criteria
- Completion and publication of app-level IA buckets and definitions
- Percentage of new feature efforts able to use the IA framework without requiring net-new placement guidance
- Qualitative feedback from feature teams indicating that placement expectations are clear earlier in delivery
- Reduction in ad hoc or escalated discussions about Home screen placement

#### Baseline KPI Values

- No single, documented IA framework exists today for app-wide feature placement
- Home screen placement expectations are not yet consistently documented
- Existing features have not been fully classified into a shared IA model
- Feature teams may rely on case-by-case alignment to determine placement

### Objectives and Key Results (OKRs)

- Establish a shared IA framework for the VA Health & Benefits mobile app
- Define clear Home screen eligibility and exclusion criteria
- Classify all existing app features into documented IA buckets
- Enable future feature teams to make placement decisions earlier and more consistently

## Solution Approach

- *What are you going to build now, and why have you decided to start there?*  
  Define a platform-level IA framework for the mobile app, including:
  - Home screen placement criteria
  - Explicit guidance on what does not belong on the Home screen
  - App-level IA buckets or categories for where features live
  - A prioritization model for Home screen hierarchy and prominence
  - A classification pass for all existing app features

  This is the right starting point because the app is continuing to grow, and shared structural guidance is needed before more features are added or reworked.

- *Why this solution / approach over other solutions / approaches?*  
  A documented framework creates consistency across teams and scales better than case-by-case decision making. It also creates a durable foundation that can be reused across future initiatives instead of revisiting the same placement questions repeatedly.

- *What have you explicitly decided to not include in this initial set of functionality, and why?*  
  This epic is focused on defining and documenting the IA framework, not on implementing broad navigation redesigns or moving all features immediately. Any downstream changes to feature placement or Home screen design can be prioritized separately after the framework is established.

- *How will the solution / approach evolve after this initial build (knowing that this will likely change as you learn from users along the way)?*  
  The framework can be refined over time based on research, analytics, and feature team feedback. It may later inform navigation changes, feature migration efforts, or more detailed standards for specific surfaces within the app.

- *Does your solution include the VA Health and Benefits mobile application? Explain why or why not.*  
  Yes. This work is specifically focused on the VA Health & Benefits mobile app and is intended to guide how features are structured and surfaced within the app, especially on the Home screen.

## Launch Strategy

- *How are Veterans and others using this product going to know it exists?*  
  This is primarily an internal platform and product-framework effort. Veterans may experience the impact through clearer, more consistent navigation and Home screen organization over time rather than through a direct announcement.

- *What marketing, outreach, or communications are necessary for this product to be successful?*  
  Internal communication and adoption are critical. The IA framework should be published in a reusable, shareable format and socialized with product, design, and engineering teams so it can be used during planning and delivery.

